### Flag 12 — Credential Access: Credential Theft Tool

The attacker deployed a renamed copy of Mimikatz to extract credentials from the Windows LSASS (Local Security Authority Subsystem Service) process. LSASS holds authentication tokens, NTLM password hashes, and in some configurations plaintext credentials for all users currently logged into the system. On an IT administrator workstation, a successful dump likely yielded credentials with domain-wide or network-wide privileges.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **Answer** | `mm.exe` |
| **True Identity** | Mimikatz — renamed to evade signature detection |
| **Initiating Process** | powershell.exe |
| **Full Command** | `"mm.exe" privilege::debug sekurlsa::logonpasswords exit` |
| **Timestamp** | Nov 19, 2025 — 19:08:26 UTC |
| **Technique** | OS Credential Dumping: LSASS Memory (T1003.001) |

**KQL Query:**
```kql
DeviceProcessEvents
| where DeviceName == "azuki-sl"
| where Timestamp > datetime(2025-11-19T18:36:00)
| where ProcessCommandLine contains "lsass"
   or FileName == "mm.exe"
   or InitiatingProcessFileName == "mm.exe"
| project Timestamp, FileName, ProcessCommandLine, InitiatingProcessFileName
| sort by Timestamp asc
```

---

### Flag 13 — Credential Access: Memory Extraction Module

The specific Mimikatz module used was `sekurlsa::logonpasswords`, which extracts plaintext passwords, NTLM hashes, and Kerberos tickets from LSASS memory for all interactively logged-on users. This module is one of the most well-known and widely used credential theft techniques in the threat actor toolkit.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **Answer** | `sekurlsa::logonpasswords` |
| **Module** | sekurlsa |
| **Command** | logonpasswords |
| **Confirmed Via** | Same query result as Flag 12 |

