### Flag 18 — Execution: Malicious Script

Shortly after initial access, PowerShell was used with execution policy bypass and a hidden window to download and execute an attack automation script from the C2 server. The script was named to mimic a Windows Update process, consistent with JADE SPIDER's pattern of masquerading malicious components as routine system activity.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **Answer** | `wupdate.ps1` |
| **Source URL** | `http://78.141.196.6:8080/wupdate.ps1` |
| **Saved To** | `C:\Users\kenji.sato\AppData\Local\Temp\` |
| **Execution Flags** | `-ExecutionPolicy Bypass -WindowStyle Hidden` |
| **Timestamp** | Nov 19, 2025 — 18:49:48 UTC (file created) |
| **Technique** | Command and Scripting Interpreter: PowerShell (T1059.001) |

The `-WindowStyle Hidden` flag ensured no PowerShell window appeared on screen, making execution invisible to any user at the machine. A companion batch script `wupdate.bat` was also downloaded as a fallback execution method.

**KQL Query:**
```kql
DeviceFileEvents
| where DeviceName == "azuki-sl"
| where Timestamp > datetime(2025-11-19T18:36:00)
| where FolderPath contains "Temp"
   or FolderPath contains "WindowsCache"
| where FileName endswith ".ps1"
   or FileName endswith ".bat"
| project Timestamp, FileName, FolderPath, ActionType
| sort by Timestamp asc
```

