## Conclusion

The Azuki Import/Export intrusion is a clear example of how a disciplined attacker can compromise an organisation using almost entirely built-in Windows tools, minimal custom malware, and patient, methodical tradecraft. From a single exposed RDP port, JADE SPIDER achieved initial access, conducted full network reconnaissance, neutralised endpoint defences, stole credentials, exfiltrated sensitive business data, established multiple layers of persistent backdoor access, expanded to additional internal targets, and attempted to cover their tracks — all within hours of the first connection, with activity continuing across multiple weeks.

The financial impact was immediate. The leaked pricing data cost Azuki a six-year shipping contract. Without this investigation, the persistent scheduled tasks, the backdoor `support` account, and the ongoing lateral movement activity would have gone undetected indefinitely.

This investigation also demonstrated an important principle of effective threat hunting: the data is always there if you know where to look. Fourteen of the twenty flags were answerable using just three queries. The key is not running more queries — it is reading every result carefully, understanding attacker behaviour patterns, and recognising when a single result is answering multiple questions at once.

